WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.099
I'm going to show you how to add

00:00:01.099 --> 00:00:03.133
authorization to an existing application

00:00:03.133 --> 00:00:04.500
using row-level security

00:00:04.533 --> 00:00:06.233
policies. We're going to be extending

00:00:06.233 --> 00:00:07.133
this email client

00:00:07.133 --> 00:00:08.833
application, originally built by Lee

00:00:08.833 --> 00:00:10.633
Robertson at Verselle, and we're going to

00:00:10.633 --> 00:00:12.233
be going pretty deep on the Postgres

00:00:12.233 --> 00:00:12.966
side. So we're going

00:00:12.966 --> 00:00:14.633
to be learning about functions, triggers,

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:16.066
security definers on

00:00:16.066 --> 00:00:17.699
roles, and setting up one-to-one

00:00:17.699 --> 00:00:19.833
relationships across tables in different

00:00:19.833 --> 00:00:21.699
schemas. If you haven't been following

00:00:21.699 --> 00:00:22.433
along with the series,

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:24.166
I'll leave a link to the full playlist in

00:00:24.166 --> 00:00:25.133
the description. But

00:00:25.133 --> 00:00:25.966
don't worry, this video can be

00:00:25.966 --> 00:00:28.000
watched without any context of what we've

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:29.333
done so far, so long as

00:00:29.333 --> 00:00:30.566
you understand what an email

00:00:30.566 --> 00:00:32.800
client looks like. And even if you don't,

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:33.966
this is it. We have a

00:00:33.966 --> 00:00:35.400
panel of folders on the left,

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:37.233
a list of emails in those folders in the

00:00:37.233 --> 00:00:38.300
middle, and then if we click

00:00:38.300 --> 00:00:39.500
one of these emails, we see

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:41.433
the content of the selected email on the

00:00:41.433 --> 00:00:42.666
right. We can send a new

00:00:42.666 --> 00:00:44.466
email or delete an existing one,

00:00:44.466 --> 00:00:46.333
and we've also added the ability to log

00:00:46.333 --> 00:00:47.766
in with GitHub. So if I log

00:00:47.766 --> 00:00:49.166
out, we'll see this "sign in

00:00:49.166 --> 00:00:51.066
with GitHub" page, and so if we try to go

00:00:51.066 --> 00:00:52.366
back to our landing page,

00:00:52.366 --> 00:00:53.266
you'll see we're automatically

00:00:53.433 --> 00:00:55.333
redirected to this login page, so we

00:00:55.333 --> 00:00:57.233
can't actually access our emails unless

00:00:57.233 --> 00:00:58.533
we sign in with GitHub.

00:00:58.533 --> 00:01:00.066
But we're not doing any filtering on

00:01:00.066 --> 00:01:01.500
these emails displayed. If we

00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:02.533
have a look at the Supabase

00:01:02.533 --> 00:01:04.300
dashboard, and then under the table

00:01:04.300 --> 00:01:06.000
editor and emails, we'll see

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.266
the IDs for our sender and our

00:01:08.266 --> 00:01:10.500
recipient are ones and twos and threes

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:12.000
and all the way up to ten. And

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.199
if we have a look at our users

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:15.300
table, we don't actually have a row for

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:17.199
our John user. And if we go over to

00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:18.599
authentication and then

00:01:18.633 --> 00:01:20.933
users, we'll see there's only one user,

00:01:20.933 --> 00:01:22.466
which is John, who used the provider

00:01:22.466 --> 00:01:23.933
GitHub. So we have two

00:01:23.933 --> 00:01:26.466
separate users tables. We have the ones

00:01:26.466 --> 00:01:27.433
that have sent and received

00:01:27.433 --> 00:01:28.833
emails, and then we have the

00:01:28.833 --> 00:01:30.599
ones who have signed in with GitHub. And

00:01:30.599 --> 00:01:31.866
if we head over to database

00:01:31.866 --> 00:01:33.733
and then schema visualizer,

00:01:33.733 --> 00:01:35.599
we can see this very cool entity

00:01:35.599 --> 00:01:37.966
relationship diagram of all of our tables

00:01:37.966 --> 00:01:38.966
and their relationships

00:01:38.966 --> 00:01:40.466
to each other. I can just zoom out

00:01:40.466 --> 00:01:42.433
slightly so we can see all of it. So the

00:01:42.433 --> 00:01:44.133
ID on our users table has

00:01:44.133 --> 00:01:46.266
a relationship to the sender ID and the

00:01:46.266 --> 00:01:48.633
recipient ID in emails, and also a

00:01:48.633 --> 00:01:49.566
relationship to the user

00:01:49.566 --> 00:01:51.766
ID in our user folders table. So this is

00:01:51.766 --> 00:01:53.866
everything in the public schema or the

00:01:53.866 --> 00:01:54.933
tables we've created

00:01:54.933 --> 00:01:56.633
for our application. But there are a

00:01:56.633 --> 00:01:57.866
collection of other schemas

00:01:57.866 --> 00:01:59.633
being managed either by Supabase

00:01:59.833 --> 00:02:02.133
or any extensions that we have enabled.

00:02:02.133 --> 00:02:03.033
And if we have a look at the

00:02:03.033 --> 00:02:04.400
auth schema, this is all the

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:06.533
complicated stuff Supabase uses to keep

00:02:06.533 --> 00:02:08.666
a track of our sessions and also our

00:02:08.666 --> 00:02:09.800
users. So this is the

00:02:09.833 --> 00:02:12.000
users table where our users are created

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.166
when they sign in with

00:02:13.166 --> 00:02:15.000
GitHub. And then back over in our

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.199
public schema, we have our users table

00:02:17.199 --> 00:02:18.633
that's linked to our emails

00:02:18.633 --> 00:02:20.099
and the rest of our application.

00:02:20.466 --> 00:02:22.233
So we want to set up a relationship

00:02:22.233 --> 00:02:25.033
across these schemas to link out to users

00:02:25.033 --> 00:02:26.566
tables. But the types

00:02:26.699 --> 00:02:30.000
for our IDs do not match our public users

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.866
ID is an int for and in our

00:02:32.866 --> 00:02:34.933
auth schema, our users tables

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:38.266
ID is a UUID. And you can only set up

00:02:38.266 --> 00:02:39.333
foreign key relationships

00:02:39.333 --> 00:02:40.666
between two columns that have

00:02:40.666 --> 00:02:43.266
the same type. So in order to link our

00:02:43.266 --> 00:02:46.099
public schemas users table to our auth

00:02:46.099 --> 00:02:47.533
schemas users table,

00:02:47.533 --> 00:02:49.466
we're going to create a new column for

00:02:49.466 --> 00:02:52.333
our public user that's of type UUID. So

00:02:52.333 --> 00:02:53.300
let's head over to the

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:55.199
table editor. And then for our users

00:02:55.199 --> 00:02:57.466
table, we want to scroll across to the

00:02:57.466 --> 00:02:58.833
end and click this plus

00:02:58.833 --> 00:03:00.933
to add a new column. The name is going to

00:03:00.933 --> 00:03:02.266
be supabase_id.

00:03:02.266 --> 00:03:03.666
We're going to click here

00:03:03.699 --> 00:03:06.466
to add a foreign key relation to the auth

00:03:06.466 --> 00:03:07.933
schema. The table we want

00:03:07.933 --> 00:03:10.233
to reference is users and the

00:03:10.233 --> 00:03:12.000
column we want to reference in the

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.400
auth.users table is the ID. If we scroll

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:15.766
down, we can also set up

00:03:15.766 --> 00:03:17.766
the behavior for what we want to do if

00:03:17.766 --> 00:03:19.933
the row is updated in the auth.users

00:03:19.933 --> 00:03:20.966
table. So in this case,

00:03:20.966 --> 00:03:22.500
we don't want to do anything. So we want

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:24.333
it to raise an error if it breaks

00:03:24.333 --> 00:03:25.199
something that's needed

00:03:25.199 --> 00:03:27.233
for that foreign key relationship. So if

00:03:27.233 --> 00:03:28.866
the ID has changed, which

00:03:28.866 --> 00:03:30.433
shouldn't ever happen, we want

00:03:30.466 --> 00:03:32.366
to get an error. However, if the

00:03:32.366 --> 00:03:35.033
auth.user is entirely removed, we could

00:03:35.033 --> 00:03:36.300
go with no action and

00:03:36.300 --> 00:03:38.400
raise an error or we could do cascade,

00:03:38.699 --> 00:03:39.733
meaning if a user is

00:03:39.733 --> 00:03:41.533
deleted from the auth.users table,

00:03:41.866 --> 00:03:43.533
we want to cascade those deletes to the

00:03:43.533 --> 00:03:44.833
public users table. So

00:03:44.833 --> 00:03:46.033
they would also be deleted,

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:48.000
but then we'd need to cascade the deletes

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:49.933
to all of their emails and

00:03:49.933 --> 00:03:51.233
all of the other tables where

00:03:51.233 --> 00:03:53.666
they're a recipient or a sender. And so

00:03:53.666 --> 00:03:55.099
it probably doesn't make sense for us to

00:03:55.099 --> 00:03:56.199
just nuke all of their

00:03:56.233 --> 00:03:57.900
existence from the entire database.

00:03:58.433 --> 00:04:00.000
Instead, we're just going to set this to

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.333
null. So if the user is

00:04:01.333 --> 00:04:03.066
deleted from the auth.users table,

00:04:03.333 --> 00:04:05.400
nothing happens to our public user, which

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:06.400
is linked to all of the

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:08.099
data of our application. It just removes

00:04:08.099 --> 00:04:08.766
that link to the

00:04:08.766 --> 00:04:10.866
auth.users table. So our public user

00:04:10.966 --> 00:04:13.500
no longer has an auth.user. And then we

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:15.000
can click save to set up that

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:16.199
relationship. And if we

00:04:16.199 --> 00:04:17.833
scroll down a little bit, we can see the

00:04:17.833 --> 00:04:19.866
type has correctly been set to UUID,

00:04:20.233 --> 00:04:20.933
which is the type of

00:04:20.933 --> 00:04:23.233
our ID in the auth.users table. The

00:04:23.233 --> 00:04:24.966
default value is going to be null. So we

00:04:24.966 --> 00:04:25.866
need to make sure that

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:28.433
allow nullable is enabled. We also want

00:04:28.433 --> 00:04:29.800
this column to be unique.

00:04:30.366 --> 00:04:31.599
So this sets up a one-to-one

00:04:31.599 --> 00:04:33.199
relationship between our public

00:04:33.199 --> 00:04:35.300
schemas.users table and our

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.333
auth.schemas.users table. So there

00:04:37.333 --> 00:04:39.400
can only be one user in the public schema

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:40.566
that references a

00:04:40.566 --> 00:04:42.266
particular user in the auth schema.

00:04:42.699 --> 00:04:44.500
So let's click save to create that new

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:46.133
column. And now anytime a

00:04:46.133 --> 00:04:48.099
new user is created in the

00:04:48.099 --> 00:04:50.966
auth.schemas.users table. So when a new

00:04:50.966 --> 00:04:52.366
user signs into our

00:04:52.366 --> 00:04:53.933
Next.js application using GitHub,

00:04:53.966 --> 00:04:56.233
a row will automatically be added to this

00:04:56.233 --> 00:04:57.166
table. And when that

00:04:57.166 --> 00:04:59.000
happens, we want to automatically

00:04:59.166 --> 00:05:01.366
create a new user in our public

00:05:01.366 --> 00:05:03.633
schemas.users table and link them up

00:05:03.633 --> 00:05:05.566
using this Supabase ID column.

00:05:05.833 --> 00:05:08.166
And we can do exactly that with a trigger

00:05:08.166 --> 00:05:09.533
function. So let's head over

00:05:09.533 --> 00:05:11.466
to database and then functions

00:05:11.666 --> 00:05:13.933
and then create a new function. The name

00:05:13.933 --> 00:05:15.366
of this one can be handle

00:05:15.366 --> 00:05:17.166
public user. The schema will be

00:05:17.166 --> 00:05:19.133
public. The return type of this one will

00:05:19.133 --> 00:05:20.533
be a trigger. We don't

00:05:20.533 --> 00:05:22.133
need any arguments. And then

00:05:22.166 --> 00:05:24.199
in the definition of our function, we

00:05:24.199 --> 00:05:26.366
need a begin and an end. So

00:05:26.366 --> 00:05:27.666
you can learn all about begin

00:05:27.666 --> 00:05:29.833
and end and postgres functions and

00:05:29.833 --> 00:05:31.666
transactions in a video we did

00:05:31.666 --> 00:05:33.366
earlier in this series. Again,

00:05:33.699 --> 00:05:35.266
link to that playlist in the description.

00:05:35.633 --> 00:05:36.733
So inside the body of

00:05:36.733 --> 00:05:38.133
our function, we want to

00:05:38.233 --> 00:05:41.400
insert a new row into the public.users

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:43.066
table. And we just want to set the

00:05:43.066 --> 00:05:44.566
supabase_id column

00:05:44.699 --> 00:05:47.033
and the user's email. So the

00:05:47.033 --> 00:05:50.866
values will be new.id. So this new

00:05:50.866 --> 00:05:52.433
variable is special to trigger

00:05:52.466 --> 00:05:54.800
functions and represents the entire row

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:56.466
that's just been created in the

00:05:56.466 --> 00:05:58.400
auth.users table. So the

00:05:58.466 --> 00:06:01.633
new.id is the ID of the user who's just

00:06:01.633 --> 00:06:03.133
signed in with GitHub and been

00:06:03.133 --> 00:06:04.400
automatically added in the

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:06.666
auth.users table. So to access their

00:06:06.666 --> 00:06:07.866
email, we can say

00:06:07.866 --> 00:06:12.599
new.raw_user_meta_data, which is a big

00:06:12.633 --> 00:06:14.599
JSON blob of all the information we get

00:06:14.599 --> 00:06:16.933
back from GitHub about this user. So we

00:06:16.933 --> 00:06:18.266
can access the email

00:06:18.266 --> 00:06:20.266
property using this dash greater than

00:06:20.266 --> 00:06:22.199
greater than symbol and then the string

00:06:22.199 --> 00:06:23.400
of the property in that

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:25.199
big JSON blob. So in this case, that's

00:06:25.199 --> 00:06:27.233
email. And then we'll add a semicolon at

00:06:27.233 --> 00:06:28.266
the end and make sure

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:30.833
we return that new variable. Now this

00:06:30.833 --> 00:06:32.466
will insert a new user into

00:06:32.466 --> 00:06:34.166
the public schema, but one may

00:06:34.166 --> 00:06:35.766
already exist if they've been the

00:06:35.766 --> 00:06:38.766
recipient of an existing email. This is

00:06:38.766 --> 00:06:40.699
tricky. I love it. So this

00:06:40.733 --> 00:06:42.433
means we need to use an upsert action,

00:06:42.666 --> 00:06:44.633
which first attempts to insert a new

00:06:44.633 --> 00:06:45.933
user, but if one already

00:06:45.933 --> 00:06:48.066
exists, it will instead update its

00:06:48.066 --> 00:06:50.699
supabase_id column to link it to that

00:06:50.699 --> 00:06:51.933
new user in the auth

00:06:51.933 --> 00:06:54.333
schema. The way we do upserts in Postgres

00:06:54.333 --> 00:06:55.800
is we first try to insert

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:57.099
that new user with those

00:06:57.099 --> 00:07:00.533
values and then on conflict of the email

00:07:00.533 --> 00:07:01.933
column. So a user already

00:07:01.933 --> 00:07:03.833
exists in our public users table

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.099
with that specific email. So in that

00:07:06.099 --> 00:07:08.133
case, we want to do an

00:07:08.133 --> 00:07:11.233
update and set the supabase_id

00:07:11.233 --> 00:07:14.033
column to equal our new .id. And the last

00:07:14.033 --> 00:07:15.800
thing we need to do is click show

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:17.033
advanced settings and

00:07:17.033 --> 00:07:19.000
then change our type of security from

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:20.433
security invoker, which

00:07:20.433 --> 00:07:21.866
we'll call it on behalf of our

00:07:21.866 --> 00:07:24.333
user. So RLS, which we'll look at soon

00:07:24.333 --> 00:07:25.366
will be enforced. We

00:07:25.366 --> 00:07:26.533
instead want to change this to

00:07:26.533 --> 00:07:28.666
security definer, which executes the

00:07:28.666 --> 00:07:30.266
function with our current level of

00:07:30.266 --> 00:07:31.333
privileges, which is the

00:07:31.366 --> 00:07:33.199
Postgres role, which we use for our

00:07:33.199 --> 00:07:34.433
Supabase dashboard. Again,

00:07:34.433 --> 00:07:35.566
we'll go into roles later,

00:07:35.566 --> 00:07:36.966
but basically if we're doing something on

00:07:36.966 --> 00:07:38.066
behalf of the user, then we

00:07:38.066 --> 00:07:39.366
want security invoker. But

00:07:39.366 --> 00:07:41.566
because this is a system action that's to

00:07:41.566 --> 00:07:42.766
do with the integrity of

00:07:42.766 --> 00:07:44.066
our database, we want to do

00:07:44.066 --> 00:07:45.900
security definer. So let's click confirm

00:07:45.900 --> 00:07:47.833
to create that function. And now we want

00:07:47.833 --> 00:07:49.000
to call that function

00:07:49.033 --> 00:07:50.900
when a new user is added to the

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:53.400
auth.users table. So let's head over to

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:54.766
the SQL editor and we can

00:07:54.800 --> 00:07:56.966
get Supabase AI to help us out. So let's

00:07:56.966 --> 00:07:58.566
say create a trigger

00:07:58.566 --> 00:08:01.233
that calls the handle_public_user

00:08:01.266 --> 00:08:04.266
function when a row is

00:08:04.266 --> 00:08:06.099
inserted into the

00:08:06.099 --> 00:08:08.300
auth.users table. And let's see what

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:10.000
it comes up with. That looks pretty good.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:11.300
Let's accept that change.

00:08:11.599 --> 00:08:13.000
So we're creating a trigger

00:08:13.033 --> 00:08:14.866
called this. We probably don't want that

00:08:14.866 --> 00:08:16.033
to be the same name as our

00:08:16.033 --> 00:08:17.433
function. So maybe we'll call it

00:08:17.433 --> 00:08:20.366
on auth user created. So after that

00:08:20.366 --> 00:08:22.233
insert takes place on the auth.users

00:08:22.233 --> 00:08:23.733
table for each row that's

00:08:23.766 --> 00:08:25.733
affected by the statement. So for each

00:08:25.733 --> 00:08:27.199
user added to the auth.users

00:08:27.199 --> 00:08:28.933
table, we want to execute the

00:08:28.933 --> 00:08:30.899
function handle_public_user. So let's

00:08:30.899 --> 00:08:31.966
click run to create that

00:08:31.966 --> 00:08:33.766
trigger and we see success no rows

00:08:33.766 --> 00:08:35.433
returned. So everything's all good. So to

00:08:35.433 --> 00:08:36.933
test this out, we can go back to our

00:08:36.933 --> 00:08:38.033
application and then

00:08:38.033 --> 00:08:39.899
sign out our user. And then in the

00:08:39.899 --> 00:08:41.266
Supabase dashboard, go to

00:08:41.266 --> 00:08:43.033
authentication and then under

00:08:43.033 --> 00:08:45.199
users, we want to find our John user and

00:08:45.199 --> 00:08:46.166
click these three dots

00:08:46.166 --> 00:08:47.833
and say delete user. This is

00:08:47.833 --> 00:08:49.199
just a warning telling us that this is

00:08:49.199 --> 00:08:50.766
permanent. And so let's click delete.

00:08:51.033 --> 00:08:51.800
Now, if we go back to

00:08:51.833 --> 00:08:53.766
our application and sign in with GitHub

00:08:53.766 --> 00:08:55.199
again, we'll see that authentication

00:08:55.199 --> 00:08:56.399
process was successful.

00:08:56.699 --> 00:08:58.300
We can see our John user there. If we go

00:08:58.300 --> 00:08:59.500
back to the Supabase

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:01.733
dashboard and then reload our users,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:03.766
we'll see that John user is back and has

00:09:03.766 --> 00:09:05.199
signed in with GitHub. And if

00:09:05.199 --> 00:09:06.766
we go over to the table editor

00:09:06.866 --> 00:09:09.033
and look at the users table, we can see

00:09:09.033 --> 00:09:10.266
our user has automatically

00:09:10.266 --> 00:09:12.066
been created and linked to the

00:09:12.066 --> 00:09:14.633
auth.users table with this Supabase ID

00:09:14.633 --> 00:09:15.899
column. But back over in

00:09:15.899 --> 00:09:16.699
our application, this still

00:09:16.733 --> 00:09:18.966
doesn't change the emails that our John

00:09:18.966 --> 00:09:20.733
user is able to see. So let's

00:09:20.733 --> 00:09:21.866
make it so that our John user

00:09:21.866 --> 00:09:24.100
is only able to see emails that he either

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:25.899
sent or received. So let's

00:09:25.899 --> 00:09:27.133
head back over to authentication

00:09:27.366 --> 00:09:29.433
and then policies. And then we want to

00:09:29.433 --> 00:09:31.100
enable RLS or row level

00:09:31.100 --> 00:09:32.933
security for the emails table. Let's

00:09:32.933 --> 00:09:35.300
click enable RLS and confirm. And we'll

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:36.300
see this one's now green

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:38.133
instead of all this yellowy orange

00:09:38.466 --> 00:09:40.300
caution stuff. So we're on the right

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:41.966
track. Now, by default, RLS

00:09:41.966 --> 00:09:43.399
automatically denies all requests

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:45.199
to the table. So no one can select,

00:09:45.399 --> 00:09:46.699
insert, update or delete

00:09:46.699 --> 00:09:48.566
any of our emails. So if we go

00:09:48.566 --> 00:09:50.500
back to our application, we can still see

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:51.633
those emails. So let's

00:09:51.633 --> 00:09:53.733
refresh and we can still see

00:09:53.733 --> 00:09:55.733
those emails. Wait, what? They're all

00:09:55.733 --> 00:09:58.899
still there. Is RLS not working? RLS is

00:09:58.899 --> 00:09:59.899
definitely enabled on

00:09:59.899 --> 00:10:01.600
the emails table and we haven't written

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:02.733
any policies to enable

00:10:02.733 --> 00:10:04.066
any of those actions. So it

00:10:04.066 --> 00:10:05.833
should definitely be denying requests to

00:10:05.833 --> 00:10:06.966
select data from the emails

00:10:06.966 --> 00:10:07.966
table. But our application

00:10:08.233 --> 00:10:10.699
isn't actually using just emails table.

00:10:10.966 --> 00:10:12.066
We're using this view for

00:10:12.066 --> 00:10:13.699
the emails with folder and

00:10:13.699 --> 00:10:15.933
users. So this joins together all of the

00:10:15.933 --> 00:10:17.566
data about the email and

00:10:17.566 --> 00:10:19.000
then a big JSON blob for

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:20.933
the recipient and the sender. And it also

00:10:20.933 --> 00:10:22.100
gives us the folder that

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:23.800
they belong to. And by default,

00:10:24.033 --> 00:10:26.600
views bypass RLS. But we can fix this

00:10:26.600 --> 00:10:27.766
pretty easily. We can

00:10:27.766 --> 00:10:29.500
toggle between the data that's

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:31.533
returned by our view and the definition,

00:10:31.533 --> 00:10:33.100
which gives us the SQL

00:10:33.100 --> 00:10:34.933
required to reconstruct that

00:10:34.966 --> 00:10:37.033
table from scratch. And we can open this

00:10:37.033 --> 00:10:38.500
one up directly in the SQL

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:39.733
editor. And now we can make

00:10:39.733 --> 00:10:42.366
some changes by saying create or replace

00:10:42.366 --> 00:10:44.233
a view called emails with

00:10:44.233 --> 00:10:45.366
folder and users. And then we

00:10:45.366 --> 00:10:48.000
can add a with clause to set

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.666
security_invoker equal to true. Now, if

00:10:50.666 --> 00:10:51.533
we run this statement,

00:10:51.533 --> 00:10:53.800
we see success, no rows returned. And if

00:10:53.800 --> 00:10:55.399
we go back to our application and

00:10:55.399 --> 00:10:56.500
refresh, we'll see our

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:58.533
John user is no longer able to see any

00:10:58.533 --> 00:10:59.766
emails because the view

00:10:59.766 --> 00:11:01.333
that selects this data is now

00:11:01.333 --> 00:11:04.233
honoring RLS. So we can see the count for

00:11:04.233 --> 00:11:05.533
each of our folders is still

00:11:05.533 --> 00:11:07.199
bypassing RLS. And if we go

00:11:07.199 --> 00:11:08.966
back to the Supabase dashboard and

00:11:08.966 --> 00:11:10.600
then the table editor, we can see that's

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:11.833
this view or folders

00:11:11.899 --> 00:11:13.899
with email count. And we can do the same

00:11:13.899 --> 00:11:15.100
thing by going over to the

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:16.866
definition and opening it in the

00:11:16.866 --> 00:11:19.333
SQL editor and again saying create or

00:11:19.333 --> 00:11:21.666
replace the view called public dot

00:11:21.666 --> 00:11:22.666
folders with email count.

00:11:22.666 --> 00:11:25.266
And we can add our with clause to say we

00:11:25.266 --> 00:11:26.600
want to set

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:28.833
security_invoker to equal true.

00:11:28.899 --> 00:11:31.033
And then if we run this one, we see

00:11:31.033 --> 00:11:32.833
success, no rows returned. And if we go

00:11:32.833 --> 00:11:33.833
back to our application

00:11:34.066 --> 00:11:36.066
and refresh, these folders are still

00:11:36.066 --> 00:11:37.433
getting that count for the

00:11:37.433 --> 00:11:39.166
number of all of the emails that

00:11:39.166 --> 00:11:41.100
exist within that folder for every user.

00:11:41.100 --> 00:11:41.899
And this is because if we

00:11:41.899 --> 00:11:42.800
have a look at our view,

00:11:42.933 --> 00:11:45.800
it's using the folders and the email

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:47.133
folders tables, both of

00:11:47.133 --> 00:11:49.033
which still don't have RLS

00:11:49.266 --> 00:11:51.266
enabled. So we can see folders, email

00:11:51.266 --> 00:11:53.366
folders. So let's start by enabling RLS

00:11:53.366 --> 00:11:54.666
for the email_folders

00:11:54.699 --> 00:11:56.399
table. This is what's being used

00:11:56.399 --> 00:11:57.699
by our count. And now if we

00:11:57.699 --> 00:11:58.566
go back to our application,

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:01.066
and refresh, we can see no more emails.

00:12:01.533 --> 00:12:02.899
And this is exactly what we

00:12:02.899 --> 00:12:04.100
want. This doesn't mean it's

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:06.600
broken. It means it's working. Remember,

00:12:06.699 --> 00:12:08.033
RLS denies all select,

00:12:08.033 --> 00:12:09.633
insert, update or delete requests.

00:12:10.066 --> 00:12:11.933
So if we want to enable one of those, we

00:12:11.933 --> 00:12:12.933
just need to write a policy

00:12:12.933 --> 00:12:14.699
to back over in the Supabase

00:12:14.699 --> 00:12:16.533
dashboard under authentication and

00:12:16.533 --> 00:12:18.433
policies. Let's start with our emails

00:12:18.433 --> 00:12:20.399
table and write a new policy.

00:12:20.399 --> 00:12:22.066
There are some templates available to get

00:12:22.066 --> 00:12:23.233
you started, or you can use

00:12:23.233 --> 00:12:24.600
the Supabase AI assistant

00:12:24.766 --> 00:12:26.266
to write these for you. But we're going

00:12:26.266 --> 00:12:27.433
to create this one from

00:12:27.433 --> 00:12:28.833
scratch so that we can talk through

00:12:28.833 --> 00:12:30.566
exactly what's going on. So the name of

00:12:30.566 --> 00:12:32.000
our policy is going to be

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.699
users can read their emails. So

00:12:34.699 --> 00:12:36.199
because this is about reading, we're

00:12:36.199 --> 00:12:38.100
going to enable the select action, we're

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:38.966
going to leave the target

00:12:38.966 --> 00:12:40.833
roles as the default, which just applies

00:12:40.833 --> 00:12:41.966
to everyone. And then for

00:12:41.966 --> 00:12:43.233
our using expression, we

00:12:43.233 --> 00:12:44.766
need to provide a statement that either

00:12:44.766 --> 00:12:47.066
evaluates to true or false. If it

00:12:47.066 --> 00:12:48.366
evaluates to true, then the

00:12:48.366 --> 00:12:50.300
user will be able to select that email.

00:12:50.533 --> 00:12:51.633
And if it evaluates to

00:12:51.633 --> 00:12:53.566
false, then RLS will just continue

00:12:53.733 --> 00:12:55.566
denying it. So if we set this to true,

00:12:55.766 --> 00:12:57.066
and then scroll down and

00:12:57.066 --> 00:12:58.533
click review, this will show us

00:12:58.533 --> 00:13:00.500
the SQL that's been generated from each

00:13:00.500 --> 00:13:01.733
of those form fields. And

00:13:01.733 --> 00:13:03.100
then if we click Save Policy,

00:13:03.166 --> 00:13:04.699
it will run it against our Postgres

00:13:04.699 --> 00:13:06.600
database. So we can confirm that this

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:07.933
policy is working by going

00:13:07.933 --> 00:13:09.266
back over to our application and

00:13:09.266 --> 00:13:10.933
refreshing. And we don't see anything.

00:13:10.933 --> 00:13:12.199
But if we go back to look

00:13:12.233 --> 00:13:14.933
at our view for emails with folder and

00:13:14.933 --> 00:13:16.566
users, and we can just look at the

00:13:16.566 --> 00:13:17.699
definition and see that

00:13:17.699 --> 00:13:19.733
it's using this email folders table,

00:13:19.733 --> 00:13:21.699
which also has RLS enabled. So let's go

00:13:21.699 --> 00:13:22.366
back to authentication

00:13:22.899 --> 00:13:24.800
and then policies. And for our email

00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:26.066
folders, let's write a new

00:13:26.066 --> 00:13:27.066
policy. Again, we'll do this

00:13:27.066 --> 00:13:29.433
one from scratch. This will be users can

00:13:29.433 --> 00:13:31.566
select email folders will

00:13:31.566 --> 00:13:33.100
enable the select action,

00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:34.899
leave the default role as public and then

00:13:34.899 --> 00:13:36.333
put true as the using

00:13:36.333 --> 00:13:37.600
expression. Now, if we scroll down

00:13:37.766 --> 00:13:40.000
and review and then save policy. Now,

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:40.899
when we go back to our

00:13:40.899 --> 00:13:42.866
application and refresh, we see

00:13:42.933 --> 00:13:44.833
our emails are back, but our John user

00:13:44.833 --> 00:13:46.466
has just been created. So they

00:13:46.466 --> 00:13:47.966
aren't the sender or receiver

00:13:48.166 --> 00:13:50.333
of any of these emails. And we don't want

00:13:50.333 --> 00:13:52.066
everyone to be able to see everyone

00:13:52.066 --> 00:13:53.399
else's emails. That's

00:13:53.399 --> 00:13:55.399
not very secure. So instead of just

00:13:55.399 --> 00:13:58.133
returning true, we want to check that the

00:13:58.133 --> 00:13:59.566
recipient_id column

00:13:59.666 --> 00:14:02.933
is equal to our current user.

00:14:02.933 --> 00:14:04.000
And we can get our current

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:05.533
user with a special Supabase

00:14:05.533 --> 00:14:08.100
function called auth.uid. But the problem

00:14:08.100 --> 00:14:09.500
is this will return us a

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:12.066
UUID. And this is the integer ID

00:14:12.066 --> 00:14:14.100
that's used by our public schema. So

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:15.399
we're going to use a sub

00:14:15.399 --> 00:14:17.199
query here to say the

00:14:17.433 --> 00:14:20.199
recipient_id is in the result set that

00:14:20.199 --> 00:14:21.899
comes back from selecting

00:14:21.899 --> 00:14:24.866
the ID from the public dot

00:14:24.866 --> 00:14:27.399
users table where the supabase_id

00:14:27.399 --> 00:14:30.266
is equal to the result of

00:14:30.266 --> 00:14:32.000
that auth.uid function.

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:34.500
So we know our Supabase user, we know

00:14:34.500 --> 00:14:36.966
the ID of our public user.

00:14:36.966 --> 00:14:38.566
And so this will kind of glue

00:14:38.566 --> 00:14:40.633
those two together. And we also want the

00:14:40.633 --> 00:14:42.066
emails where they are the

00:14:42.066 --> 00:14:43.066
sender. So we can do the same

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:46.100
thing and say or sender_id is

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:47.500
in and then copy and paste

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:49.199
that same sub query. And now

00:14:49.199 --> 00:14:51.199
if we click review, we'll see the SQL

00:14:51.199 --> 00:14:52.633
that's been generated to alter

00:14:52.633 --> 00:14:54.533
our policy and save policy to

00:14:54.533 --> 00:14:56.633
run that SQL against our database. And

00:14:56.633 --> 00:14:57.699
now if we go back to our

00:14:57.699 --> 00:14:59.566
application and refresh, we'll see

00:14:59.666 --> 00:15:01.733
no emails because our John user hasn't

00:15:01.733 --> 00:15:03.333
received or sent any emails.

00:15:03.633 --> 00:15:04.933
So we can go back over to the

00:15:04.933 --> 00:15:07.699
table editor and go to emails and change

00:15:07.699 --> 00:15:09.333
the sender for this first

00:15:09.333 --> 00:15:11.066
email to be our John user,

00:15:11.266 --> 00:15:13.633
and then change the recipient of this one

00:15:13.633 --> 00:15:15.100
to also be our John

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:16.500
user. Now when we go back to

00:15:16.533 --> 00:15:19.033
our application and refresh, we see one

00:15:19.033 --> 00:15:20.933
email in our inbox, which is weird

00:15:20.933 --> 00:15:21.633
because it's sent both

00:15:21.666 --> 00:15:23.600
from me to me, but that's fine. And then

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:24.666
if we look in our sent

00:15:24.666 --> 00:15:26.600
emails, we see one email that's been

00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:28.566
sent so we can see our numbers are still

00:15:28.566 --> 00:15:29.666
off for each of these

00:15:29.666 --> 00:15:31.233
folders. And that's because in our

00:15:31.233 --> 00:15:34.033
RLS policy, so over in authentication and

00:15:34.033 --> 00:15:35.333
then policies, our select

00:15:35.333 --> 00:15:36.666
policy on our email folders

00:15:36.699 --> 00:15:39.500
table is still just using the expression

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:41.066
true. So since we always

00:15:41.066 --> 00:15:42.666
want the number of emails in

00:15:42.666 --> 00:15:44.633
that folder to match the number of emails

00:15:44.633 --> 00:15:45.733
we can select from that

00:15:45.733 --> 00:15:47.166
folder, we can actually use this

00:15:47.166 --> 00:15:49.033
little trick to enforce policies from

00:15:49.033 --> 00:15:50.633
another table. So we can

00:15:50.633 --> 00:15:53.300
say select star from emails

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:56.600
where email_id matches the

00:15:56.600 --> 00:15:58.600
emails tables ID. And now

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:00.166
since the RLS policies from

00:16:00.166 --> 00:16:02.500
the emails table are going to be enforced

00:16:02.500 --> 00:16:04.166
on this select statement,

00:16:04.166 --> 00:16:05.466
our user is only going to get

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:07.466
back records that the policies on the

00:16:07.466 --> 00:16:09.666
emails table allows them to. So another

00:16:09.666 --> 00:16:10.833
little efficiency tip

00:16:10.833 --> 00:16:12.433
here is rather than actually selecting

00:16:12.433 --> 00:16:13.366
those columns, we can

00:16:13.366 --> 00:16:15.000
just select the number one,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:16.633
which represents true. And then we can

00:16:16.633 --> 00:16:18.033
wrap this in an exist

00:16:18.033 --> 00:16:19.866
statement. If we get back the value

00:16:19.866 --> 00:16:21.566
true from this select statement, then

00:16:21.566 --> 00:16:23.733
this entire policy will return true.

00:16:23.733 --> 00:16:24.833
Otherwise it will return

00:16:24.833 --> 00:16:26.833
false. Again, because this requires a

00:16:26.833 --> 00:16:28.433
user to be authenticated, we can set it

00:16:28.433 --> 00:16:29.333
to the authenticated

00:16:29.333 --> 00:16:31.833
role to ensure it only runs for users who

00:16:31.833 --> 00:16:32.766
are signed in. Now we can

00:16:32.766 --> 00:16:34.199
click review to see the SQL

00:16:34.233 --> 00:16:36.600
for our policy and save policy to run it.

00:16:36.600 --> 00:16:37.433
And now if we go back to

00:16:37.433 --> 00:16:38.866
our application and refresh,

00:16:39.133 --> 00:16:41.199
we'll see we only have that one email in

00:16:41.199 --> 00:16:42.466
our inbox, which is this one

00:16:42.466 --> 00:16:43.933
and that one email in our sent

00:16:43.933 --> 00:16:46.300
folder, which is this one. Wow, that was

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:47.633
a little bit complex. If

00:16:47.633 --> 00:16:49.533
you're new to RLS, if it didn't

00:16:49.533 --> 00:16:51.566
quite click, just take the video back and

00:16:51.566 --> 00:16:53.000
watch it again. You can do

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.600
that as many times as you want.

00:16:55.166 --> 00:16:57.800
Okay. So our users are able to select the

00:16:57.800 --> 00:16:59.833
emails that they are the sender or

00:16:59.833 --> 00:17:01.233
recipient of, but what

00:17:01.266 --> 00:17:03.333
if they try to delete an email? It looks

00:17:03.333 --> 00:17:04.433
like it's no longer selected

00:17:04.433 --> 00:17:05.899
here, but it still exists here

00:17:05.899 --> 00:17:07.533
and it still exists here. So I don't

00:17:07.533 --> 00:17:08.733
think it's actually gone. Let's try

00:17:08.733 --> 00:17:09.933
refreshing. Yep. Still

00:17:09.933 --> 00:17:11.366
there. And we can click it and still see

00:17:11.366 --> 00:17:12.733
its contents. So delete is

00:17:12.733 --> 00:17:13.899
not working. And you know

00:17:13.899 --> 00:17:17.000
why it's RLS. We wrote a select policy,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.666
but if we want to enable the delete

00:17:18.666 --> 00:17:19.833
action, we need to write

00:17:19.833 --> 00:17:21.733
a policy for it. So back over in the

00:17:21.733 --> 00:17:23.566
Supabase dashboard on our emails

00:17:23.566 --> 00:17:24.866
table, we want to create

00:17:24.866 --> 00:17:26.500
a new policy. Again, we'll do this one

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:28.366
from scratch. The name is going to be

00:17:28.366 --> 00:17:30.033
user can delete their

00:17:30.066 --> 00:17:32.199
emails. It's going to enable the delete

00:17:32.199 --> 00:17:34.033
action. The target roles is going to be

00:17:34.033 --> 00:17:35.000
set to authenticated.

00:17:35.433 --> 00:17:37.133
And then for our using expression, it

00:17:37.133 --> 00:17:38.433
probably only makes sense

00:17:38.433 --> 00:17:39.699
for a user to be able to delete

00:17:39.699 --> 00:17:41.300
emails that they sent rather than

00:17:41.300 --> 00:17:43.233
received. So we want to check that the

00:17:43.233 --> 00:17:45.399
sender_id is in

00:17:45.399 --> 00:17:47.766
this sub query where we select the ID

00:17:47.766 --> 00:17:50.899
from the public dot users table where the

00:17:50.899 --> 00:17:52.000
supabase_id

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.899
is equal to the auth.uid function. So

00:17:54.899 --> 00:17:56.066
let's scroll down, click

00:17:56.066 --> 00:17:57.366
review and then save policy.

00:17:57.600 --> 00:17:59.300
And if we go back to our application and

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:00.633
try to delete this email

00:18:00.633 --> 00:18:02.166
in our inbox, it's not going

00:18:02.166 --> 00:18:03.766
to work because remember we are the

00:18:03.766 --> 00:18:05.333
recipient. But if we go to our sent

00:18:05.333 --> 00:18:07.066
emails and try to delete

00:18:07.066 --> 00:18:08.600
this one, let's click that little delete

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:09.800
button again, it's no

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:11.266
longer selected, but it's still

00:18:11.266 --> 00:18:12.733
here in our list. So what's going on

00:18:12.733 --> 00:18:14.833
here? Well, we've written a delete policy

00:18:14.833 --> 00:18:15.833
for the emails table.

00:18:16.066 --> 00:18:17.933
And if we have a look in the table editor

00:18:17.933 --> 00:18:19.033
for our email folders

00:18:19.033 --> 00:18:21.666
table, our email ID column has a

00:18:21.666 --> 00:18:24.166
foreign key relationship to our emails ID

00:18:24.166 --> 00:18:25.833
and on delete it's

00:18:25.833 --> 00:18:27.233
cascading. So whenever we delete

00:18:27.300 --> 00:18:29.399
a row from the emails table, it's going

00:18:29.399 --> 00:18:31.899
to cascade down to our email folders

00:18:31.899 --> 00:18:33.166
table. So we can go here

00:18:33.166 --> 00:18:35.066
to get back to our policies and then just

00:18:35.066 --> 00:18:36.366
remove this search term to

00:18:36.366 --> 00:18:37.899
see all of our tables. So if

00:18:37.899 --> 00:18:40.333
we have a policy for delete on our emails

00:18:40.333 --> 00:18:42.000
table, we also need a delete

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:43.533
policy on our email folders

00:18:43.533 --> 00:18:45.300
table. So let's create a new policy.

00:18:45.300 --> 00:18:46.666
We'll do this one from scratch. It's

00:18:46.666 --> 00:18:48.699
going to enable delete for

00:18:48.866 --> 00:18:50.600
sender. It's going to enable the delete

00:18:50.600 --> 00:18:52.666
action. We're going to select the

00:18:52.666 --> 00:18:53.633
authenticated role and

00:18:53.666 --> 00:18:55.666
then for our using expression, we're

00:18:55.666 --> 00:18:58.433
going to select star from the emails

00:18:58.433 --> 00:19:00.000
table where the email_id

00:19:00.066 --> 00:19:02.199
column matches our

00:19:02.199 --> 00:19:04.533
emails.id. So this will give us back the

00:19:04.533 --> 00:19:05.433
email we're trying to

00:19:05.433 --> 00:19:07.833
delete. We then want to select the

00:19:07.833 --> 00:19:09.500
sender_id. So again,

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:11.833
this is the integer ID from our

00:19:11.833 --> 00:19:13.633
public users table. So if we want to

00:19:13.633 --> 00:19:14.733
match that against our

00:19:14.733 --> 00:19:16.300
currently signed in user, we need to

00:19:16.300 --> 00:19:18.100
get their Supabase ID. So we'll come

00:19:18.100 --> 00:19:19.266
back to this one and say

00:19:19.266 --> 00:19:21.533
select supabase_id

00:19:21.666 --> 00:19:24.566
from the public dot users table where the

00:19:24.566 --> 00:19:27.300
ID is in this sub query,

00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:29.033
which will be this select. So we

00:19:29.033 --> 00:19:31.500
have the sender ID of the email. We're

00:19:31.500 --> 00:19:33.633
then looking up that ID in the public dot

00:19:33.633 --> 00:19:34.699
users table and then

00:19:34.699 --> 00:19:36.166
just pulling out the supabase_id

00:19:36.166 --> 00:19:38.666
column. So lastly, we just

00:19:38.666 --> 00:19:39.566
want to check is the

00:19:39.566 --> 00:19:42.266
result of the auth dot UID function in

00:19:42.266 --> 00:19:44.333
another sub query, which is going to be

00:19:44.333 --> 00:19:45.500
this whole select. So

00:19:45.533 --> 00:19:48.933
we can move this one inside this one and

00:19:48.933 --> 00:19:50.033
we can fix up our

00:19:50.033 --> 00:19:52.233
indentation. And now we're only

00:19:52.233 --> 00:19:54.533
enabling delete for the sender of that

00:19:54.533 --> 00:19:55.866
email. So let's scroll down,

00:19:55.866 --> 00:19:57.266
click review and save policy.

00:19:57.500 --> 00:19:58.766
And now when we go back to our

00:19:58.766 --> 00:20:01.233
application and select one of our emails

00:20:01.233 --> 00:20:02.533
in the send folder and

00:20:02.533 --> 00:20:04.533
attempt to delete it, we can see it's

00:20:04.533 --> 00:20:06.000
disappeared from our selected

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:07.333
email. It's also disappeared

00:20:07.333 --> 00:20:09.199
from our list and our email folders.

00:20:09.533 --> 00:20:11.233
Awesome. We can select and we can delete

00:20:11.233 --> 00:20:12.133
emails, but what about

00:20:12.233 --> 00:20:13.866
sending a new one? Well, we're about to

00:20:13.866 --> 00:20:15.133
run into exactly the same

00:20:15.133 --> 00:20:16.866
problem with RLS. So we need a

00:20:16.866 --> 00:20:18.866
new policy for insert just to make this a

00:20:18.866 --> 00:20:20.000
little easier. We can edit

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.500
our delete policy and copy

00:20:21.666 --> 00:20:24.133
our expression and then create a new

00:20:24.133 --> 00:20:25.800
policy again from scratch.

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:28.066
This one will be users can insert

00:20:28.233 --> 00:20:30.866
their own emails. This will enable the

00:20:30.866 --> 00:20:32.233
insert action. The target

00:20:32.233 --> 00:20:33.800
role can be set to authenticated.

00:20:34.066 --> 00:20:35.866
And then for our with check expression,

00:20:35.866 --> 00:20:37.199
we want to check the same as

00:20:37.199 --> 00:20:38.800
our delete policy. So if the

00:20:38.866 --> 00:20:41.133
sender of the email is the same user as

00:20:41.133 --> 00:20:42.166
our currently signed in

00:20:42.166 --> 00:20:43.399
user, then we want to allow

00:20:43.399 --> 00:20:44.966
them to insert that row because it

00:20:44.966 --> 00:20:46.433
wouldn't make sense for them to send an

00:20:46.433 --> 00:20:47.733
email with someone else

00:20:47.899 --> 00:20:50.066
set as the sender. Let's review and save

00:20:50.066 --> 00:20:51.066
this policy and we can

00:20:51.066 --> 00:20:52.266
do the same for our email

00:20:52.266 --> 00:20:54.433
folders table. So let's edit our delete

00:20:54.433 --> 00:20:55.699
policy, copy this same

00:20:55.699 --> 00:20:58.100
expression, then create a new policy

00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:00.933
from scratch. That's going to allow user

00:21:00.933 --> 00:21:04.133
to insert email into folder. It's going

00:21:04.133 --> 00:21:05.133
to enable the insert

00:21:05.166 --> 00:21:06.866
action. The target role will be

00:21:06.866 --> 00:21:08.699
authenticated and then our with check

00:21:08.699 --> 00:21:10.033
expression will be the same as

00:21:10.033 --> 00:21:11.500
our delete policy. So again, we're

00:21:11.500 --> 00:21:13.666
walking back the relationship tree from

00:21:13.666 --> 00:21:14.800
our email folders table

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:17.300
where we know the email ID that the user

00:21:17.300 --> 00:21:18.266
is currently trying to

00:21:18.266 --> 00:21:19.933
insert. We then work our way

00:21:19.933 --> 00:21:22.699
back up to the Supabase ID for that

00:21:22.699 --> 00:21:24.766
user and check if that's the user who's

00:21:24.766 --> 00:21:25.766
currently signed in.

00:21:25.766 --> 00:21:28.033
Let's click review and save policy. And

00:21:28.033 --> 00:21:29.033
one more thing before we

00:21:29.033 --> 00:21:30.399
can actually send our email,

00:21:30.533 --> 00:21:32.666
we need to go over to database and then

00:21:32.666 --> 00:21:34.866
functions. And then for our send email

00:21:34.866 --> 00:21:35.833
function, we want to

00:21:35.833 --> 00:21:37.600
click these three dots and edit our

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:39.466
function. And if we scroll down, we can

00:21:39.466 --> 00:21:40.566
see the definition of

00:21:40.566 --> 00:21:42.800
our function and where we're inserting a

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:44.000
new email, you can see

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:45.466
we're setting the sender ID

00:21:45.500 --> 00:21:48.033
column to the static value one. And

00:21:48.033 --> 00:21:48.833
that's because in the

00:21:48.833 --> 00:21:50.333
initial template from Lee,

00:21:50.333 --> 00:21:52.633
we didn't have authentication yet. And so

00:21:52.633 --> 00:21:53.966
we could declare another

00:21:53.966 --> 00:21:55.633
variable like we did earlier to

00:21:55.666 --> 00:21:57.800
hold our sender's ID. But since we're

00:21:57.800 --> 00:21:58.966
super comfortable with

00:21:58.966 --> 00:22:00.699
sub queries, we can do this

00:22:00.699 --> 00:22:04.133
in line by selecting the ID from the

00:22:04.133 --> 00:22:06.833
users table where the supabase_id

00:22:06.833 --> 00:22:08.666
column matches

00:22:08.666 --> 00:22:11.566
the result of our auth.uid function. So

00:22:11.566 --> 00:22:12.933
again, we know our Supabase ID,

00:22:12.933 --> 00:22:14.800
but we want to look up

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:17.500
our integer ID from the public schemas

00:22:17.500 --> 00:22:18.899
users table. So just to be

00:22:18.899 --> 00:22:20.300
more clear, we could prepend this

00:22:20.399 --> 00:22:22.933
with public dot users. And then this

00:22:22.933 --> 00:22:25.766
integer ID is what we want to insert as

00:22:25.766 --> 00:22:26.899
the sender ID column

00:22:26.933 --> 00:22:28.800
on the new email. And so let's click

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:31.266
confirm to update our send email

00:22:31.266 --> 00:22:32.566
function. And then back over

00:22:32.566 --> 00:22:34.866
in our application, we can send a new

00:22:34.866 --> 00:22:36.233
email to a user who doesn't

00:22:36.233 --> 00:22:37.566
exist in our application yet. So

00:22:37.566 --> 00:22:39.766
we could say jon@supabase.io,

00:22:39.766 --> 00:22:42.033
the subject can be does this

00:22:42.033 --> 00:22:44.233
work and the body can be, I sure

00:22:44.366 --> 00:22:46.966
hope so. And when we click send, we'll

00:22:46.966 --> 00:22:48.500
see our send folder now has

00:22:48.500 --> 00:22:49.800
two items, one of which is

00:22:49.833 --> 00:22:51.699
our john user. And because we are the

00:22:51.699 --> 00:22:53.333
sender, we can delete this

00:22:53.333 --> 00:22:54.833
one and it disappears from our

00:22:54.833 --> 00:22:57.366
emails and also our number of sent

00:22:57.366 --> 00:22:59.266
emails. And this is only just

00:22:59.266 --> 00:23:00.766
scratching the surface of why

00:23:00.766 --> 00:23:03.166
RLS is awesome and how powerful it can be

00:23:03.166 --> 00:23:03.800
to implement

00:23:03.800 --> 00:23:05.666
authorization rules in the database

00:23:05.666 --> 00:23:07.699
itself. If you want to go deeper with

00:23:07.699 --> 00:23:09.100
RLS, I recommend you check

00:23:09.100 --> 00:23:10.433
out this video right here,

00:23:10.433 --> 00:23:12.733
we go through a bit more theory on RLS

00:23:12.733 --> 00:23:14.000
and slowly work up to a

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.966
similar example of enforcing RLS

00:23:15.966 --> 00:23:18.399
policies from other tables. But until

00:23:18.399 --> 00:23:20.533
next time, keep building cool stuff.

